column5: I've been poking around in the wawa area and have seen some ok places. Only down side would be that I've heard that most of those lake have been fished out. Wondering if anyone has fished in that area lately or have some info on it.
We went on a fly in to little missanabiIt's was goodOur outfitter wasn't great but the lake was great with the opurtunity to fish two other lakes

My buddy and I have fished White Lake (70 miles wast of Wawa) the last 5 years in mid June! All I can say is the north end of the lake is outstanding for eyes. Staying in the provincial park and running 12-15 miles to Clay Bay for the best fishing. If weather cooperates you can expect to boat 20-30 fish by late morning. Many times we had trouble catching small eyes for dinner. Most fish run 20-25". For more info hit me back.
Which mode of transportation were you considering to reach your destination? Depending on what you are looking for there can be many options available to you.
By car Or boat in. It would be with my personal boat too.
Doug white lake supposed to be a secret. Lol! One morning a buddy and I must have caught 50 walleyes in three hours. Fisherman 1792

According to MNR data White Lake is the most productive walleye lake in that region, including fly in lakes. Not sure about that, but it's definitely one of the largest.Over the years I've never fished it, but have heard it's very good.

I fished little miss in summer of 14. Group of 6 of us, caught almost 2k fish over the week. Probably my favorite lake in that area. Also fished Easey Point in 2012. It was good, but not nearly as good as Little Miss.We are trying Mosambik this year..
I dont have a link but i know James Smedley wrote an article in ontario out of doors about a camping trip on white lake
